classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Introduction to Civil Engineering
classes.description: Freshman orientation course for the Civil Engineering program the professiona nd an introduction to the University. Introduction to the tools for civil engineering studies: internet word processing and spreadsheets. Development of communication skills and the ability to work in teams. Development of learning skills in civil engineering studies. 1 hour lecture/discussion 3 hours lab per week.

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Introduction to Civil Engineering Lab
classes.description: Freshman orientation course for the Civil Engineering program the professiona nd an introduction to the University. classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Computer Applications in Civil Engineering
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 240. Development of computer skills related to the field of civil engineering. Introduction of Windows email and internet usage. Introduction to Office suite word processing spreadsheets with VBA applications presentation and publishing software. Development of programming skills. Application of CAD to the development of structural and architectural drawings dimensioning grading plans contour lines and sections. Analysis and design of structural systems using structural engineering packages. Development of algorithms and computer codes for the solution of civil engineering problems. 1hour of lecture 3 hours of lab per week.

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Structural Steel Design
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 335. Basic concepts in the design of steel structures. Design in steel of tension and compression members beams columns welded and bolted connections; eccentrically loaded and moment resistant joints; plate girders. Introduction to computer aided design (CAD). (Design units: 3.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Engineering Statics
classes.description: Prerequisite: PHYS 220A/L. Corequisite: MATH 150B. Analysis of the distribution of forces on and within bodies in static equilibrium. Free body diagrams equilibrium equations and the method of sections. Includes a limited introduction to the subject of strength of materials. (Design units: 0.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Strength of Materials
classes.description: Prerequisites: CE 240; MATH 280. Analysis of the stresses and deflections in members and basic structural systems. Axial torsional bending and shear stresses and deflections. Introduction to structural stability. Design of structural components. (Design units: 0.5)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Reinforced Concrete Design
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 335. Basic concepts in the design of reinforced concrete structures. Applications to beams columns slabs shear walls footing and composite construction. (Design units: 3)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Engineering Hydrology
classes.description: Prerequisite: ME 390. Corequisite 460L. Surface Hydrology for the design of drainage flood control water storage and distribution systems. Topics include hydrologic cycle meteorology surface and ground water movement interrelation between precipitation and runoff hydrograph analysis flood routing and risk assessment. Hydrologic model development and analysis using computers emphasized for design of storm drainage systems flood protection water storage and reservoir operations. 2 hours lecture 3 hours lab. (Design units: 1.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Engineering Hydrology Lab
classes.description: Prerequisite: ME 390. Corequisite 460. Surface Hydrology for the design of drainage flood control water storage and distribution systems. Topics include hydrologic cycle meteorology surface and ground water movement interrelation between precipitation and runoff hydrograph analysis flood routing and risk assessment. Hydrologic model development and analysis using computers emphasized for design of storm drainage systems flood protection water storage and reservoir operations. 2 hours lecture 3 hours lab. (Design units: 1.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Surveying
classes.description: Corequisite: 308L. Fundamentals of plane and geodetic surveying. Concepts of linear and angular measurements precision errors and corrections. Field problems in chaining differential and profile leveling triangulation and highway curves. 2 hours lecture 3 hours lab. (Design units: 0.)

classes.title: Surveying Lab

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Structures I
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 340. Corequisite: CE 335L. Determination of the force distribution and deflections in statically determinant and indeterminant structures using the classical non-matrix methods of structural analysis. 3 hours of lecture per week. Lab: Structural analysis problem solving session. Computer applications of structural analysis and design. 3 hours of lab per week. (Design units: 0)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Structures I Computational Lab
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 340. Corequisite: CE 335. Determination of the force distribution and deflections in statically determinant and indeterminant structures using the classical non-matrix methods of structural analysis. 3 hours of lecture per week. Lab: Structural analysis problem solving session. Computer applications of structural analysis and design. 3 hours of lab per week. (Design units: 0)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Timber and Masonry Design
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 335. Study of vertical and lateral loading on structures. Elements of timber design. Timber beams tension members compression members tension and bending and compression and bending members. Design of horizontal diaphragms and shearwalls. Design of connections. Elements of masonry design. Design of masonry in bending shear and axial members. 4 hours of lecture. (Design units: 4.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Soil Mechanics
classes.description: Corequisite: 426L. Soil as a foundation for structures and as a material of construction. Lab experiments to be performed to obtain data to determine soil physical properties. 3 hours lecture 3 hours lab per week. (Design units: 1.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Soil Mechanics
classes.description: Corequisite: 426L. Soil as a foundation for structures and as a material of construction. Lab experiments to be performed to obtain data to determine soil physical properties. 3 hours lecture 3 hours lab per week. (Design units: 1.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Geotechnical Foundation Design
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 426. Soil mechanics aspects of foundation design. Shear strength and compressibility of soil. Lateral pressures and retaining structures. Strength and deformation laws for spread footings piers piles and caissons. Analysis of mat foundations. Eccentric and inclined foundation loads. (Design units: 1.0.)

classes.title: Soil Mechanics Lab

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Civil Engineering Senior Design II
classes.description: Prerequisite: CE 488A/L. Corequisites: Second major civil design course either CE 438 439 or 526. Continuation of CE 488A. (CE 488A and CE 488B must be completed within the same academic year.) Final design stage of the project initiated in CE 488A is undertaken with emphasis on working in project teams. 6 hours of lab per week. (Offered Spring semester.) (Design units: 2.)

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Independent Study
classes.description: Prerequisite:s Senior or graduate standing in Civil Engineering with senior or graduate program on file; Written approvals of faculty sponsor and Department Chair. Admission based on evidence of ability to pursue Independent Study in-depth and approval of a proposal submitted prior to registration in the course. (Design units vary.)

classes.title: Directed Comprehensive Studies

classes.subject: CE
classes.title: Earthquake Engineering
classes.description: Prerequisites: AM 410; CE 335. Study of the earthquake problem. Topics covered include plate tectonics seismology dynamic response of structures dynamics of sites and design for earthquakes.
